 {id:'actuary', map:'manoir', name:'The Actuary', emoji:'📐', los:['2.3.2a','2.3.2b','2.3.2c','2.3.6b','2.3.6c','2.3.6e'], c:4, r:6, lines:()=>[
   "I run Lord DB's numbers. His assets sit in TWO BUCKETS: the HEDGING bucket tracks liabilities and minimizes surplus volatility (long-duration bonds, inflation-linked bonds, longevity derivatives); the GROWTH bucket chases returns above liability growth to cut future sponsor contributions.",
   "Three ways to run the hedge: DURATION MATCHING (targets interest-rate risk, needs constant rebalancing), CASH FLOW MATCHING (match inflows to outflows — purer, but instruments rarely line up), and the OVERLAY approach (derivatives/swaps — no need to sell growth assets, but it adds leverage).",
   "Four factors drive liability risk: INTEREST RATES (the big one — they set the PBO discount rate; falling rates inflate liabilities), inflation (COLA), the retirement cycle, and mortality/longevity. Five factors set the SPONSOR's tolerance: funded status, fund size vs sponsor assets, future contributions vs expected cash flows, financial position (D/E), and participant demographics — younger pool, higher tolerance.",
   "For retirees I price three risks: LONGEVITY, MARKET, INFLATION. Expected economic life: EL = −1/ln(1+R) × ln[(payment − R×assets)/payment]. A 62-year-old with $1.5M drawing $135k at 4.5% real: 15.75 years — broke by 78. Cut the draw to $100k: 25.53 years.",
   "And the GROWTH ANNUITY: PV = initial payment/(r − g) × [1 − ((1+g)/(1+r))^n]. Example: $20,000 growing 2%, discounted at 6%, 20 years → $268,337. Memorize the shape of that formula."
 ]},
