 /* ===== V4 MVO Tower ===== */
 {id:'mvoWizard', los:['3.1.1a','3.1.1b','3.1.1c','3.1.1d','3.1.2a','3.1.2b','3.1.2c','3.1.2d'], map:'mvohub', name:'Mean-Variance Wizard', emoji:'🧙‍♂️', c:2, r:2, lines:()=>[
   "Strategic asset allocation is long-term and preference-driven. Tactical asset allocation is short-term and opportunistic. Topic 3 constantly contrasts those two.",
   "Utility spell #1: E[u] = mean − (lambda/2 × variance). Positive lambda = risk-averse; zero = risk-neutral; negative = risk-seeking. Higher lambda means a lower risky-asset weight.",
   "Utility spell #2: alternatives often need higher moments. Investors dislike variance, like positive skewness, and dislike kurtosis. A VaR version can replace variance with VaR.",
   "Optimization spell: w = (1/lambda) × excess return / variance for one risky asset plus cash. With growing liabilities, add the liability correlation term: more positive covariance with liability growth can justify more risky exposure.",
   "Exam correction: MVO optimizes WEIGHTS. Expected return, variance, covariance and risk aversion are inputs. Do not answer 'portfolio returns' again."
 ]},
 {id:'errorGoblin', los:['3.1.3b','3.1.4a','3.1.4b','3.1.4c','3.1.4d','3.1.6d'], map:'mvohub', name:'Error-Maximizer Goblin', emoji:'👹', c:10, r:2, lines:()=>[
   "Optimizers love bad inputs. Exaggerate a mean return or understate volatility and I will create absurd positive and negative weights. That is why MVO is called an ERROR MAXIMIZER.",
   "Illiquid alternatives make me stronger: quarterly smoothed returns understate variance and covariance, so the optimizer overweights them. Unsmoothing usually reveals higher volatility and lower returns.",
   "Higher-moment trap: MVO may prefer a higher-mean asset even when it has ugly negative skew. Fixes: change the optimizer to include skew/kurtosis, add skew/kurtosis constraints, or cap assets with NEGATIVE skew / high tail risk. Do NOT cap positive skew as the supposed fix.",
   "Common fix danger: throwing subjective constraints at the model can make the constraints drive the allocation more than the best risk-return estimates."
 ]},
 {id:'objectiveSage', los:['3.1.6a','3.1.6b','3.1.6c'], map:'mvohub', name:'Objective Methods Sage', emoji:'🧠', c:2, r:6, lines:()=>[
   "Blank-answer repair: objective estimation-error tools include RESAMPLING and SHRINKAGE, plus Black-Litterman.",
   "Resampling: repeatedly optimize using simulated hypothetical returns or samples drawn from the original sample with replacement. Replacement means an extreme month can appear more than once.",
   "Shrinkage reduces sample variation by narrowing confidence intervals or imposing a structure, such as equal correlations. Ledoit-Wolf style shrinkage tries to avoid purely subjective tinkering.",
   "Black-Litterman blends market equilibrium with investor views. Its common constraints include limiting correlation with a benchmark, limiting deviation from benchmark weights, and limiting weight ranges. It is NOT primarily a factor-exposure limit tool."
 ]},
 {id:'hurdleKeeper', los:['3.1.3c'], map:'mvohub', name:'Hurdle Keeper', emoji:'🚧', c:10, r:6, lines:()=>[
   "A new asset earns a place only if its expected excess return beats the hurdle: E[Rnew] − Rf > (E[Rp] − Rf) × beta_new.",
   "Beta zero? Then it only needs expected return above the risk-free rate. Negative beta hedges can qualify even with low or negative expected returns if the hedge benefit is strong enough."
 ]},
 /* ===== V4 TPA HQ ===== */
 {id:'tpaArchitect', los:['3.2.1a','3.2.2a','3.2.2b','3.2.2c','3.2.3a'], map:'tpahq', name:'TPA Architect', emoji:'👷‍♀️', c:2, r:2, lines:()=>[
   "Traditional institutional models are criticized for BUCKETING, misaligned incentives, and poor response to dynamic markets. Asset-class buckets can create an illusion of diversification.",
   "TPA combines four dimensions: governance, factor lens, competition for capital, and culture. The goal is long-term TOTAL PORTFOLIO optimization, not bucket-level victory.",
   "The reference portfolio is the board's simple risk/return benchmark — for example 70% global equities and 30% global bonds over rolling five years. Helpful, but not always mandatory.",
   "TPA vs SAA: portfolio-level goals rather than asset-class benchmarks; total return rather than relative value; factor diversification rather than bucket diversification; collaborative teams rather than silos.",
   "Governance nuance: the board empowers investment teams but retains fiduciary obligations. The board moves up to risk, return, geopolitics, inflation, positioning and strategy attractiveness."
 ]},
 {id:'factorCoach', los:['3.2.4a','3.2.4b'], map:'tpahq', name:'Four-Step Factor Coach', emoji:'🧑‍🏫', c:10, r:2, lines:()=>[
   "Your constructed-response repair: the four factor implementation steps are RISK targets, EXPOSURE targets, STRATEGY targets, EXECUTION management.",
   "Step 1: the board sets risk targets/budget using the reference portfolio and market as a guide. Step 2: the CIO/core team sets exposure targets — the critical factor mix.",
   "Step 3: strategies are mapped to the desired factors, not just asset-class labels. Step 4: every investment/divestment and rebalancing decision is executed against the total-portfolio factor map; derivatives can serve as a strategic overlay.",
   "Challenges: complexity, model error, private-asset lag/smoothing, the flat max problem, benchmark banality, and factor attribution being less intuitive to stakeholders."
 ]},
 {id:'capitalJudge', los:['3.2.5a','3.2.5b'], map:'tpahq', name:'Capital Arena Judge', emoji:'⚖️', c:2, r:6, lines:()=>[
   "In TPA, every existing holding and every new idea competes for scarce capital at the total-portfolio level. A toll road can compete with a global macro fund if both serve the same portfolio need.",
   "This is more dynamic than annual SAA bucket budgets. Every marginal dollar asks: what is the opportunity cost? What is the best use within liquidity, risk and resource limits?",
   "Challenges: information overload, difficulty re-running optimization for every idea, constant review burden, finite resources, and liquidity demands such as capital calls or derivative collateral calls."
 ]},
 {id:'cultureSmith', los:['3.2.6a','3.2.6b','3.2.7a','3.2.7b'], map:'tpahq', name:'Culture Smith', emoji:'🛠️', c:10, r:6, lines:()=>[
   "TPA culture needs long-term focus AND agility. Short-term dislocations are opportunities only if the organization can move without abandoning the long-term mission.",
   "Implementation is top-down: collaboration, communication, cross-functional forums, redesigned support services and compensation tied to long-term portfolio-level outcomes.",
   "Best-practice themes: reference portfolio, absolute/portfolio-level orientation, risk budget framework, organization redesign, dashboard/data/rebalancing agility, and culture alignment.",
   "Three myths: a reference portfolio is required; only absolute-return funds can use TPA; technical skills matter more than soft skills. Preconditions: accept change, define the reason for adoption, and commit for years."
 ]},
 /* ===== V4 Risk Budget Gym ===== */
 {id:'coreCoach', los:['3.3.1a','3.3.2a','3.3.7a'], map:'riskgym', name:'Core-Satellite Coach', emoji:'🧢', c:2, r:2, lines:()=>[
   "Core-satellite repair: CORE = low-cost passive indices, strategic allocation, risk-averse stability. SATELLITE = active management, tactical allocation, risk-seeking alpha pursuit.",
   "Your miss: the satellite does NOT use strategic allocation. It uses TAA. Core uses SAA.",
   "Top-down starts with macro, country, sector and currency context. Bottom-up starts with fund/security screening and due diligence. Mixed combines both. Young PE shops often start bottom-up, then move toward mixed/top-down as their deal closet deepens.",
   "TAA is a temporary deviation from SAA to exploit short- or medium-term expected outperformance when benefits exceed trading, tax and management costs."
 ]},
 {id:'riskBudgeter', los:['3.3.3a','3.3.3b','3.3.4a','3.3.4b'], map:'riskgym', name:'Risk Budgeter', emoji:'📏', c:10, r:2, lines:()=>[
   "Risk budgeting sets an aggregate risk level, then allocates risk across buckets such as equity risk, rate risk, credit risk, illiquidity risk, VaR, beta, tracking error or active risk.",
   "Important trap: expected return may not enter until the final optimization step. A manager not expected to generate alpha should receive no active risk budget — use passive funds instead.",
   "Risk contribution decomposes into three attributes: correlation with portfolio, volatility, and weight. Contribution = rho_i × sigma_i × weight_i.",
   "Factor risk allocation strength: target specific risk exposures. Weaknesses: limited global access, short-selling constraints, no guarantee of superior returns, and bundled factors that are hard to isolate."
 ]},
 {id:'parityMonk', los:['3.3.5a','3.3.5b','3.3.5c','3.3.5d','3.3.6b'], map:'riskgym', name:'Risk Parity Monk', emoji:'🧘', c:2, r:6, lines:()=>[
   "Risk parity equalizes marginal risk contributions. It considers correlations, not only volatility, so low-volatility assets often receive higher weights.",
   "Your process error: the three steps are define risk, measure marginal risk contribution, then determine weights by trial and error. It is NOT 'calculate weights using MVO'.",
   "Why low-volatility assets may not have lower returns: leverage aversion. Investors dislike leverage, so they under-demand low-volatility assets; prices fall, Sharpe ratios rise. This links to the volatility anomaly and betting-against-beta.",
   "Criticisms: historical relationships can change, funding liquidity can force deleveraging, and evidence may not extend cleanly to alternatives.",
   "Equivalence repair: equal volatility + unequal correlations means EQUAL WEIGHTING and INVERSE VOLATILITY weighting produce the same weights. Risk parity would differ because it uses correlation."
 ]},
 {id:'taaModeler', los:['3.3.6a','3.3.6c','3.3.8a','3.3.8b'], map:'riskgym', name:'TAA Modeler', emoji:'🤖', c:10, r:6, lines:()=>[
   "Other quant strategies: market-weighted, equal-weighted 1/N, inverse-volatility weighted, and minimum-volatility. Alternatives make market weighting hard because market size and double-counting are messy.",
   "Sound TAA models need economically meaningful signals, absence of data mining, and avoidance of overfitting. A very high in-sample R-squared can be a warning sign, not a badge of quality.",
   "Unconditional SAA uses historical mean returns, volatilities and correlations. Conditional TAA uses current variables — such as dividend yield or term spread — to generate conditional expected returns.",
   "Technical TAA signals can supplement fundamentals. Example: increase exposure above a moving average and reduce it below — but transaction costs can shrink apparent outperformance."
 ]},
 /* ===== V4 Private Markets Harbor ===== */
 {id:'cashCaptain', los:['3.4.1a','3.4.1b'], map:'peharbor', name:'Cash Call Captain', emoji:'🧑‍✈️', c:2, r:2, lines:()=>[
   "Private funds call capital when deals appear. Too much idle cash creates drag; too little cash creates default risk if an LP misses a capital call.",
   "Overcommitment ratio = total commitments / resources available for commitments. Under 100% is inefficient; 125% to 140% is often reasonable in practice.",
   "The optimal overcommitment ratio minimizes idle-cash opportunity cost plus expected illiquidity/default costs. Cash-flow models help forecast calls, distributions, risk and economic value."
 ]},
 {id:'liquidVendor', los:['3.4.2a','3.4.2b','3.4.2c'], map:'peharbor', name:'Liquid Alt Vendor', emoji:'🧃', c:10, r:2, lines:()=>[
   "Liquid alternatives put alternative strategies into more liquid, regulated vehicles. Growth drivers: DC retirement shift and demand for diversification when bonds/equities look unattractive.",
   "Your clone trap: a fund mimicking an existing hedge fund but adding liquidity/leverage/diversification limits is a CONSTRAINED CLONE. Liquidity-based replication instead chooses liquid assets with similar characteristics to illiquid securities.",
   "Regulatory constraints: leverage, diversification, and liquidity limits. Return differences vs private placements come from no incentive fees, possibly less skilled managers, no illiquidity premium, and narrower permitted strategies."
 ]},
 {id:'coinvestBroker', los:['3.4.3a','3.4.3b','3.4.4a','3.4.4b','3.4.5a','3.4.5b'], map:'peharbor', name:'Co-Invest Broker', emoji:'🤝', c:2, r:5, lines:()=>[
   "Direct investment models: SOLO investing, PARTNERSHIP investing, and CO-INVESTMENT. Co-investing is the most popular direct-investing format because it leverages the GP at lower fees.",
   "LP challenges: in-house program cost, access to co-investments, reduced diversification, organizational constraints. GP challenges: LP lack of follow-through, deal delays, special-purpose vehicle/reporting costs, and relationship issues with non-co-investing LPs.",
   "Your trap: regulatory approvals for each co-investment are NOT the standard challenge listed here.",
   "Three co-investing structures: direct in a main-fund company, GP-controlled top-up fund, or case-by-case program. Side letters may include lock-step provisions; bridging finances the time before co-investor ownership.",
   "Advantages include lower fees, targeted investing, improved monitoring and reduced J-curve. Disadvantages include concentration, fiduciary risk, conflicts, LP disagreement and fee-allocation disputes. Successful LPs need expertise, GP network, fast approval, and risk management."
 ]},
 {id:'secondaryAppraiser', los:['3.4.6a','3.4.6b','3.4.6c'], map:'peharbor', name:'Secondary Appraiser', emoji:'🧾', c:10, r:5, lines:()=>[
   "Secondary buyers like discounts and portfolio visibility. Sellers may need liquidity, rebalance strategically/tactically, escape disappointing returns, lock in gains, or manage the denominator effect.",
   "Large endowments usually source through intermediated auctions. Large portfolios may be split, and a second auction round may follow after buyers review more information.",
   "Valuation: present value the projected net cash flows using the buyer's required IRR, then discount = (NAV − price) / NAV. Your miss: PV $4.632m vs NAV $5.3m gives 12.6%, not 13.1%.",
   "Limitations: secondaries do not transform risk management, and the market is still small relative to primary PE. In stress, liquidity can disappear exactly when wanted most."
 ]},
 {id:'continuationGP', los:['3.4.7a','3.4.7b'], map:'peharbor', name:'Continuation Fund GP', emoji:'🧳', c:6, r:6, lines:()=>[
   "GP-led secondaries: continuation funds, fund recaps, NAV lending, and other equity structures such as SPVs or annex funds. Continuation funds are the dominant format.",
   "A continuation fund buys assets from a maturing legacy fund and gives legacy LPs choices: cash out, roll over, partial cash/roll, or add capital.",
   "Risk repair: continuation funds can distort GP fundraising optics by making an extension look like a timely successful exit. Both GP and LPs incur transaction/due-diligence costs.",
   "Conflict risk is strongest around valuation, especially with new LPs and a reset basis. Reset basis lets the GP crystallize old carry; if the continuation fund later loses money, old carry is not clawed back."
 ]},
 /* ===== V4 Rebalancing Dojo ===== */
 {id:'rebalSensei', los:['3.5.1a','3.5.1b','3.5.2a','3.5.2b'], map:'rebaldojo', name:'Rebalancing Sensei', emoji:'🥋', c:5, r:2, lines:()=>[
   "Buy-and-hold is passive and has a LINEAR payoff. As equities rise, equity weight and portfolio volatility rise. It fits investors whose risk tolerance rises with wealth.",
   "Constant mix rebalances back to target weights. It sells winners and buys losers: contrarian, CONCAVE payoff, no floor, risk tolerance independent of wealth.",
   "Random walk: rebalancing does not change expected payoff but changes risk. Trending: rebalancing lowers expected payoff while controlling risk. Mean-reverting: rebalancing improves expected payoff.",
   "Even without mean reversion, reducing variance can lift geometric return because compound return roughly equals arithmetic return minus one-half variance."
 ]},
 {id:'cppiGuard', los:['3.5.3a','3.5.3b','3.5.3c'], map:'rebaldojo', name:'CPPI Floor Guard', emoji:'🛡️', c:2, r:5, lines:()=>[
   "CPPI formula: floor = present value of required future value; cushion = portfolio value − floor; target risky investment = M × cushion. M > 1 makes it portfolio insurance; CPPI is momentum-like.",
   "Your calculation repair: at t0, equity = 1.3 × (135 − 100) = 45.50. At t1, equity grows to 45.50 × 135/124 = 49.54 and portfolio value is 139.04. Target equity = 1.3 × (139.04 − 100) = 50.75, so buy 1.21.",
   "Risks: gap risk if markets fall faster than rebalancing; absorption risk if cushion hits zero and the portfolio misses a rebound. Variations: dynamic multiplier, resetting the floor/TIPP, and stop loss."
 ]},
 {id:'obpiAlchemist', los:['3.5.4a','3.5.4b','3.5.5a','3.5.6a','3.5.6b'], map:'rebaldojo', name:'OBPI Alchemist', emoji:'🧪', c:8, r:5, lines:()=>[
   "OBPI uses options for portfolio insurance. Protected put = long stock + long put. Put-call parity says that can be replicated with long call + risk-free bond.",
   "If options are expensive or unavailable, dynamic replication can approximate the put with a bond plus short delta units of stock. Benefits: no OTC counterparty, no embedded option risk premium. Costs: rebalancing, gap risk, and delta-estimation risk.",
   "Illiquid assets can be rebalanced using liquid futures proxies, but imperfect correlation creates tracking error. Futures position depends on alpha, beta, expected futures return, target risky weight and current illiquid weight.",
   "Manager replacement cost: foregone loss carryforward. If a fund falls from 100 to 80, the old manager earns no incentive fee until NAV is above 100; a new manager resets the high-water mark and charges sooner. Staying also has costs: stale incentives and concentration risk if others redeem."
 ]},
 /* ===== V3 exterior (topic-wide: industry, client-first) ===== */
 {id:'econ', los:['1.1.1a','1.1.2a','1.1.4b','1.2.2d'], map:'world3', name:'Value Chain Economist', emoji:'🧑‍💼', c:3, r:5, lines:()=>[
   "Welcome to the ETHICS VILLAGE — Topic 1, the capital. I map the whole investment industry: principals, agents, stakeholders, and the value chain that links them.",
   "Value creation should be judged by stakeholder impact over extended time — shareholder value, shared value, and systems value are the three lenses.",
   "The client-first reading also names three industry characterizations to contrast: MISALIGNED, PROFESSIONAL, and UNNECESSARY industry. Know which trademarks belong to which.",
   "The equation carved on the obelisk over there sums up the topic: Purpose + Professionalism + Assurance = Value."
 ]},
 {id:'trust', los:['1.1.4a','1.1.4b','1.1.4c','1.1.4d','1.1.4e'], map:'world3', name:'Trust Broker', emoji:'🤝', c:10, r:14, lines:()=>[
   "I trade in the only currency that matters here: TRUST. The client trust triad: Credibility + Communication + Professionalism.",
   "When the right choice is NOT obvious, weigh three situations: conflicts of interest, benefit-cost tradeoffs, and insufficient knowledge of the client.",
   "For conflicts, run the IDMRP process: Identify, Disclose, Manage or avoid, Recuse if necessary, Prioritize client interests.",
   "That is the client-first mindset in action — the virtuous circle where trust feeds alignment, and alignment feeds value."
