  w:["Replicating a value factor at low cost","High leverage on a broad index","A regulatory illiquidity premium"],
  why:"True alpha = beating the market without any discernible style tilt; purest form: positive return with zero correlation to indices."},
 {lo:'4.2.2', d:'E', q:"MANUFACTURED ALPHA comes from:", a:"Unlocking value in the underlying investment",
  w:["Replicating an index","Other investors' forced selling","Passively holding beta"],
  why:"It comes from unlocking value in the underlying (typical of PE)."},
 {lo:'4.2.2', d:'M', q:"Source of TRANSITIONAL ALPHA during the 2007–2009 GFC:", a:"Natural buyers forced to sell (downgrades, IPS/regulatory constraints)",
  w:["PE multiple expansion","Rising policy rates","The growth of ETFs"],
  why:"Downgrades → forced selling → buying at fire-sale prices → mean reversion when natural buyers return."},
 {lo:'4.2.3', d:'M', q:"Transitional alpha vs Inaccessible Risk Premium — the key difference:", a:"Duration of the price distortion (short vs long)",
  w:["Public vs private","Levered vs unlevered","Liquid vs illiquid"],
  why:"Transitional = SHORT-lived distortion; IRP = LONG-lived (buyer pool limited by regulation)."},
 {lo:'4.2.3', d:'E', q:"Examples of ALTERNATIVE BETA:", a:"Cat bonds, merger arb, trend following",
  w:["Concentrated zero-correlation stock picking","LBO with operational restructuring","AAA government bonds"],
  why:"Rules-based strategies that became liquid and accessible (cat bonds, merger arb, trend following, interval funds)."},
 {lo:'4.2.3', d:'M', q:"Why is alternative beta NO LONGER classified as alpha?", a:"It became rules-based, replicable, and accessible at low cost",
  w:["Its returns turned negative","Regulation banned it","It requires too much skill"],
  why:"Competition + academic publication slid it down the pyramid into low-cost retail products."},
 {lo:'4.2.1', d:'E', q:"The TWO continua of the hierarchy-of-alpha pyramid:", a:"Number of managers and price elasticity",
  w:["Risk and return","Liquidity and duration","Dispersion and correlation"],
  why:"Horizontal = number of managers; vertical = price elasticity (fees)."},
 {lo:'4.2.1', d:'M', q:"PERSISTENCE of alpha across markets:", a:"PE: 5–10 years; HF: months–years; public: near zero",
  w:["Public: 5–10 years; PE: none","Identical everywhere (~3 years)","HF: 10 years; PE: 6 months"],
  why:"Public markets: no persistence. Hedge funds: months to a few years. Private equity: 5–10 years — evidence of process/skill."},
 {lo:'4.2.1', d:'M', q:"Due-diligence focus at the TOP of the pyramid:", a:"The manager's skill and expertise",
  w:["The strategy's cost","The investment process","Tracking error"],
  why:"Top → skill; middle → process; base (pure beta) → cost."},
 {lo:'4.1.1', d:'H', q:"$200M portfolio, β=0.9, target β=1.35, βfutures=1. Futures position?", a:"Long $90M",
  w:["Short $90M","Long $45M","Short $270M"],
  why:"1.35 = 0.9 + (F/200M)×1 → F = +$90M. Target > current → LONG."},
 {lo:'4.1.1', d:'H', q:"Portable alpha: Russell 2000 expected at +400 bps, $25M allocated within a $250M portfolio. Ported alpha?", a:"40 bps",
  w:["400 bps","4 bps","100 bps"],
  why:"400 bps × (25/250) = 40 bps at the total-portfolio level."},
 {lo:'4.1.2', d:'M', q:"Put-call parity: long stock + long put + short call =", a:"A riskless bond",
  w:["A straddle","A synthetic forward","A collar"],
  why:"+Stock + Put − Call = riskless bond."},
 {lo:'4.1.2', d:'M', q:"Delta of a PUT (Black-Scholes):", a:"N(d1) − 1",
  w:["N(d1)","1 − N(d2)","−N(d2)"],
  why:"Call delta = N(d1); put delta = N(d1) − 1."},
 {lo:'4.1.2', d:'M', q:"An options trader is NET LONG options when:", a:"Implied vol < expected vol",
  w:["Implied vol > expected vol","Delta is zero","The market is rising"],
  why:"Options are volatility bets: long when implied < expected."},
 {lo:'4.2.4', d:'M', q:"Components of the PE return bridge:", a:"Revenue growth, margin, multiple expansion, leverage",
  w:["Dividends, coupons, capital gains, FX","Alpha, beta, gamma, vega","Carry, roll, spot, collateral"],
  why:"R-M-M-L — disaggregate each to separate skill from market/industry effects."},
 {lo:'4.2.1', d:'E', q:"The 'holy grail' of pure alpha:", a:"Positive returns with zero correlation to broad indices",
  w:["Beating the index by 50 bps a year","Zero fees","Zero volatility"],
  why:"Improbable on a consistent basis — hence the dusty trophy in the Alpha House."},
 {lo:'4.1.3', d:'H', q:"Delta hedging a CORRECTLY priced option: expected payoff of the hedge?", a:"Zero",
  w:["Risk-free rate × premium","Always positive","Equal to theta"],
  why:"Long option + short delta×shares: correctly priced → zero payoff; mispriced → arbitrage."},
 {lo:'4.1.1', d:'H', q:"Portable alpha relies mainly on:", a:"Derivatives to hunt alpha outside the beta's benchmark",
  w:["Short selling the benchmark only","Unlisted illiquid assets","Raising cash"],
  why:"Alpha and beta are separated: beta managed cheaply, alpha hunted on another benchmark via derivatives."},
 {lo:'4.2.5', d:'M', q:"Per the Bailey criteria, a useful benchmark must be:", a:"Unambiguous, measurable, investable, specified in advance, agreed to by the manager, same style",
  w:["Kept secret until the evaluation period ends","Composed only of illiquid assets","Recomputed after the fact based on performance"],
  why:"Bailey: unambiguous, measurable, investable, specified in advance, agreed to, reflective of current opinion, same style — your SUMO mnemonic."},
 {lo:'4.2.5', d:'M', q:"Preferred benchmark for a liquid alternatives (LAI) fund:", a:"A peer group of the same style",
  w:["A long-only equity index","The risk-free rate","Any low-correlation index"],
  why:"Long-only equity indices correlate poorly with LAIs; a same-style peer group is preferred — though it may not be investable if member funds are closed."},
 {lo:'4.2.6', d:'H', q:"In a single-factor regression of excess returns, the manager's alpha is:", a:"The intercept, if statistically significant",
  w:["The slope of the regression","The regression R²","The average residual"],
  why:"Alpha = intercept, beta = slope; only a statistically significant alpha evidences value added (or destroyed if negative)."},
 {lo:'4.2.8', d:'M', q:"Why is the CAPM unfit for alternative investments?", a:"Non-normal returns, illiquidity, investor-specific holdings, heterogeneous preferences",
  w:["Because alternatives' beta is always zero","Because it assumes high management fees","Because alternatives carry no systematic risk"],
  why:"Asymmetric distributions (skew/kurtosis), transaction costs, undiversified idiosyncratic positions, heterogeneous horizons → multifactor models needed."}, {lo:'4.1.4', d:'M', q:"The three key observations on delta-hedging:", a:"Not a directional bet; profits from derivative-vs-underlying mispricing; partly a volatility bet",
  w:["Directional, leveraged, and tax-driven","Always riskless in efficient markets","Only viable for puts"],
  why:"Delta hedging is not directional; in efficient markets it exploits mispricings between derivative and underlying; and it is partly a bet on volatility."},
 {lo:'4.1.4', d:'M', q:"Delta-neutral portfolios should be rebalanced MORE frequently when:", a:"Autocorrelations are negative (mean-reverting prices) — net of transaction costs",
  w:["Autocorrelations are positive (trending)","Options are deep out-of-the-money","Volatility is zero"],
  why:"Negative autocorrelation → frequent rebalancing pays (mind costs); positive (trending) → rebalance infrequently. Best results: short-dated, near-the-money options."},
 {lo:'4.1.5', d:'M', q:"Rebalancing with mean-reverting assets enhances:", a:"The geometric mean return, via volatility reduction — not the expected value",
  w:["The expected value of the portfolio","Only the Sharpe ratio","The arithmetic mean of each asset"],
  why:"Volatility reduction boosts geometric (compound) returns but not expected value. Ideal assets: high volatility, low correlation, mean-reverting — commodities."},
 {lo:'4.1.5', d:'E', q:"The classic asset profile that best rewards rebalancing:", a:"High volatility, low correlation, mean-reverting prices (commodities)",
  w:["Low volatility, high correlation, trending","Zero-coupon bonds","Buy-and-hold mega-cap equities"],
  why:"Commodities typically combine all three traits — the sweet spot for harvesting diversification return."},
 {lo:'4.1.2', d:'E', q:"Options traders treat the underlying stock as:", a:"A slack variable used to adjust delta exposure",
  w:["A directional bet","A volatility hedge","Collateral for margin only"],
  why:"Non-traders use options directionally; traders bet on volatility and use the underlying merely to tune delta."},
 {lo:'4.1.3', d:'M', q:"The binomial option framework used for delta hedging is built in:", a:"A risk-neutral world",
  w:["A risk-averse world with utility weights","The real-world measure only","A zero-volatility world"],
  why:"The stock-and-call tree is constructed under risk neutrality; a properly priced call then admits a zero-payoff delta-neutral hedge."},
 {lo:'4.3.1', d:'E', q:"A commodity index that holds a FIXED QUANTITY of each commodity (like the S&P 500 fixes share counts) is:", a:"Quantity-based",
  w:["Value-based","An excess return index","Third-generation by definition"],
  why:"Fixed quantities = quantity-based; fixed percentage weights of index value = value-based. Sector weights can use world production, liquidity, or open interest."},
 {lo:'4.3.1', d:'M', q:"TOTAL RETURN vs EXCESS RETURN commodity index — the difference is:", a:"Total return adds the collateral yield (fully collateralized); excess return is the futures position only",
  w:["Total return includes dividends, excess return does not","Excess return adds the roll yield, total return excludes it","They differ only in rebalancing frequency"],
  why:"Total return = futures return + collateral yield. Excess return = futures position return only."},
 {lo:'4.3.1', d:'H', q:"In a BACKWARDATED market, a LONGER holding-period assumption on the futures curve leads to:", a:"A higher roll return",
  w:["A lower roll return","Zero roll return","Negative roll return by construction"],
  why:"Backwardation → positive roll return, and it is amplified at the far end of the curve. 1st-gen indices (S&P GSCI) roll early at the near end; newer indices hold longer."},
 {lo:'4.3.1', d:'M', q:"THIRD-generation commodity indices differ from first-generation because they:", a:"Add active commodity selection via objective rules or discretion",
  w:["Only hold front-month energy contracts","Remove collateral yield","Are always short the curve"],
  why:"1st gen: energy-heavy, long-only front month, prespecified rolls. 2nd gen: forward curve positioning. 3rd gen: adds active selection."},
 {lo:'4.3.2', d:'M', q:"The most suitable benchmark for DISCRETIONARY CTAs is:", a:"Peer groups",
  w:["The MLM algorithmic trend index","Long-only futures contracts","A pure equity beta index"],
  why:"Algorithmic indices (like MLM's 252-day moving average system) suit TREND-FOLLOWING CTAs; long-only misses short exposure; peer groups fit discretionary CTAs despite data problems."},
 {lo:'4.3.2', d:'M', q:"Evidence on trend-following CTA returns shows that:", a:"More than half of historical excess return is NOT explained by passive exposures",
  w:["Beta explains nearly all excess return","They correlate highly with long-only commodity indices","They correlate highly with equities"],
  why:"Beta return is less than half of total excess return; trend-following and discretionary CTAs have low correlations with traditional assets AND long-only commodity indices."},
 {lo:'4.3.3', d:'M', q:"The key drawback of a LISTED PE index (e.g., LPX 50) as a benchmark:", a:"It reflects GP-level cash flows and fees and behaves statistically like public equities, not like the underlying LP assets",
  w:["It cannot be computed daily","It excludes management fees entirely","It only covers venture capital"],
  why:"Publicly traded PE firm returns resemble other public equities — not the return distribution of the underlying private assets."},
 {lo:'4.3.3', d:'H', q:"A PE fund shows KS-PME = 1.26x. Interpretation:", a:"The fund outperformed the public index — hypothetical distributions are 26% larger than the hypothetical contribution portfolio",
  w:["The fund underperformed the index by 26%","The fund's IRR is 26%","The index returned 1.26% annually"],
  why:"KS-PME = hypothetical distributions ÷ hypothetical portfolio of capital calls. 1.0 = match; >1.0 = PE outperformance; <1.0 = underperformance."},
 {lo:'4.3.3', d:'H', q:"The LN-PME method becomes INEFFECTIVE when:", a:"The PE fund massively outperforms the index, driving the hypothetical portfolio into a short position",
  w:["The fund has more than five capital calls","The index pays dividends","The fund lasts more than 10 years"],
  why:"Large distributions vs a weaker index push the hypothetical portfolio negative (short); later index gains enlarge the short. KS-PME was developed to fix this."},
 {lo:'4.3.4', d:'M', q:"When too few PE funds share a vintage/geography/stage for a peer cohort, best practice is to:", a:"Broaden the peer definition (e.g., country → region)",
  w:["Skip benchmarking entirely","Compare to the S&P 500 instead","Use only the single largest fund"],
  why:"Peer cohorts need similar vintage year, geography, development stage, specialization; if the cohort is too thin, widen the definition. Quartile rankings also vary by metric (IRR/PME/multiple) and window."},
 {lo:'4.3.5', d:'M', q:"The cap rate (NOI ÷ value) used to benchmark core real estate is:", a:"An UNLEVERED return measure that ignores income growth and capital appreciation",
  w:["A levered total return","A growth-adjusted total return","Net of capital expenditures and financing costs"],
  why:"NOI is pre-leverage (like EBIT), so cap rate is unleveraged; it ignores growth potential and appreciation — a starting point, not a complete return."},
 {lo:'4.3.5', d:'M', q:"Typical US CORE real estate cap-rate spread over the default-free 10-year yield:", a:"2%–3%",
  w:["0%–0.5%","5%–7%","8%–10%"],
  why:"Cap rate spread = cap rate − 10Y default-free yield; US core typically 2–3%. Historic core cap rates ranged roughly 5–10%."},
 {lo:'4.3.5', d:'M', q:"Best approach for estimating expected returns on NONCORE (value-added/opportunistic) real estate:", a:"A risk premium added relative to core real estate",
  w:["An absolute hurdle rate","Observed noncore cap rates (reliable data)","The REIT index return"],
  why:"Absolute hurdles ignore the inflation/rate environment; noncore cap-rate data is unreliable; so add risk premiums to the core cap rate."},
 {lo:'4.4.1', d:'M', q:"An investor deposits $200,000 with a CTA; fees and returns are computed on $350,000. Notional funding is:", a:"$150,000",
  w:["$200,000","$350,000","$550,000"],
  why:"Trading level ($350k) = funding level ($200k) + notional funding ($150k). Fees/returns are calculated on the trading level — the leverage magnifies gains and losses."},
 {lo:'4.4.1', d:'E', q:"The MARGIN-TO-EQUITY ratio of a CTA measures:", a:"Assets held as margin relative to NAV — a proxy for leverage and fund volatility",
  w:["Cash relative to management fees","Initial margin relative to maintenance margin","Realized volatility over implied volatility"],
  why:"Higher margin-to-equity = more leverage = more volatility. At 90%, equity barely covers the margin requirement."},
 {lo:'4.4.1', d:'M', q:"A CROSS-MARGIN benefit arises when:", a:"Related positions clear on the SAME exchange, so total margin is below the sum of individual margins",
  w:["Positions are spread across many clearinghouses","Margin is posted in several currencies","Variation margin is settled weekly"],
  why:"Globally diversified CTAs on multiple clearinghouses lose the benefit and face currency issues — single-currency margining is one fix. Variation margin is the DAILY settlement of gains/losses."},
 {lo:'4.4.1', d:'M', q:"Capital at Risk (CaR) for managed futures is best described as:", a:"The total loss if EVERY position hits its stop-loss on one day — likely overstating risk since long/short offsets make simultaneous stops unlikely",
  w:["The guaranteed maximum loss of the fund","The one-day 99% VaR","The margin call amount at a 5-sigma move"],
  why:"CaR sums stop-loss losses across positions; in practice prices can slip PAST the stop (a stop becomes a market order), yet offsetting long/short books make all-stops-at-once unlikely."},
 {lo:'4.4.2', d:'M', q:"A portfolio has a one-day VaR of $1M at 99% confidence. This means:", a:"There is a 99% probability the daily loss will NOT exceed $1M — expect a worse day about once per 100 trading days",
  w:["The maximum possible daily loss is $1M","Losses of $1M occur every day","Expected daily profit is $1M"],
  why:"VaR is a loss threshold at a confidence level, not a maximum. On $50M, this VaR is 2%."},
 {lo:'4.4.2', d:'H', q:"Daily mean 0.025%, daily σ 1.25%, 95% confidence (α = −1.645). Daily parametric VaR:", a:"2.03%",
  w:["1.25%","1.65%","2.53%"],
  why:"VaR = (α × σ) + μ = (−1.645 × 1.25%) + 0.025% = −2.03% → reported as 2.03%. Requires a normal return distribution."},
 {lo:'4.4.2', d:'M', q:"In exponentially weighted variance estimation, setting λ CLOSE TO 1:", a:"Puts more weight on recent observations",
  w:["Puts more weight on distant observations","Equal-weights all observations","Removes the mean from the estimate"],
  why:"λ near 1 → recent returns dominate the updated mean and variance; useful when volatility changes over time."},
 {lo:'4.4.3', d:'H', q:"Notional contract value $100,000; one-σ price move 1.5%; initial margin $12,500 doubles in the stress test. Total cash required in a 5-sigma scenario:", a:"$32,500 (32.5% of base)",
  w:["$7,500","$25,000","$20,000"],
  why:"5-sigma loss = $100,000 × (1.5% × 5) = $7,500; new margin = $25,000; total = $32,500. Positive excess kurtosis makes such moves less rare than a normal distribution implies."},
 {lo:'4.4.3', d:'H', q:"Monthly returns exceed target by 1,2,2,4,5,6,7% and fall short by 3,4,5,7,11%. The omega ratio is:", a:"0.90",
  w:["1.11","0.27","1.00"],
  why:"Omega = ΣUPM / ΣLPM = 27% / 30% = 0.90. Below 1.0 → total returns fall short of target. Omega falls with higher vol, higher kurtosis, lower skew, or a higher target."},
 {lo:'4.4.4', d:'M', q:"Price smoothing UNDERSTATES all of the following EXCEPT:", a:"Long-term mean return",
  w:["Volatility","Correlation with the market","Beta"],
  why:"Smoothing mutes outliers, lowering σ, correlation, and beta — but long-term means are largely unaffected. Result: smoothed assets get overweighted and hedge ratios go wrong."},
 {lo:'4.4.4', d:'M', q:"Smoothed prices persist (are not arbitraged away) mainly because:", a:"Appraisals are not tradable bids/offers, and transaction costs or barriers block the arbitrage",
  w:["Regulators prohibit unsmoothing","Arbitrageurs prefer smoothed returns","Smoothing only exists in bear markets"],
  why:"No true trading opportunity exists on an appraisal, and costs (commissions, taxes, redemption fees) exceed potential gains — so unsmoothing must be done statistically."},
 {lo:'4.4.5', d:'H', q:"With decay parameter α = 0.50, a $5 rise in the REPORTED price implies the TRUE price is:", a:"$10 above the previous reported price",
  w:["$5 above the previous reported price","$2.50 above the previous reported price","Unchanged"],
  why:"P_true = P(t−1),reported + (1/α)×ΔP_reported = 2 × $5 = $10. Private real estate α≈0.40 → true changes ≈2.5× reported changes."},
 {lo:'4.4.5', d:'M', q:"Appraisers relying too heavily on previous valuations — one of the four causes of index autocorrelation — is called:", a:"Anchoring",
  w:["Front-running","Sterilization","Mean reversion"],
  why:"Four causes: stale component prices, appraiser anchoring, biased transaction prices, and the lag between price-setting and closing/reporting."},
 {lo:'4.4.6', d:'H', q:"Reported returns: 0%, then 4.4%. With ρ = 0.45, the unsmoothed (true) return for the second period is:", a:"8.0%",
  w:["4.4%","6.4%","2.4%"],
  why:"R_true = (R_rep − ρ×R_prev,rep)/(1−ρ) = (4.4% − 0)/(0.55) = 8%. Three steps: assume AR(1), estimate ρ = corr(Rt, Rt−1), apply the formula."},
 {lo:'4.4.7', d:'H', q:"Smoothed annual variance 0.025, autocorrelation 30%. TRUE variance:", a:"0.046 (volatility ≈ 0.215)",
  w:["0.019","0.025","0.033"],
  why:"σ²true = σ²rep × (1+ρ)/(1−ρ) = 0.025 × 1.30/0.70 = 0.046. Unsmoothing raises risk estimates — NPI true volatility was >3× its smoothed value."},
 {lo:'4.4.7', d:'H', q:"A smoothed return series has β = 0.55 and ρ = 0.40. The TRUE beta is approximately:", a:"0.92",
  w:["0.33","0.55","1.38"],
  why:"βtrue = βrep/(1−ρ) = 0.55/0.60 ≈ 0.92. With positive autocorrelation, smoothed series always understate systematic risk."},
 {lo:'4.4.7', d:'M', q:"NPI vs NAREIT as real estate benchmarks:", a:"NPI is appraisal-based and heavily smoothed (ρ≈85%); NAREIT uses market prices and proxies true returns (ρ≈12%)",
  w:["NAREIT is appraisal-based; NPI is market-based","Both have identical autocorrelation","NPI reflects leverage; NAREIT does not"],
  why:"NPI lagged the 2008–09 crash and recovery; NAREIT (leveraged, market-priced) moved in real time. Unsmoothing the NPI roughly doubled its correlations to NAREIT and the Russell 3000."},
 {lo:'4.5.1', d:'M', q:"In the five components of risk measurement, the question 'WHEN?' corresponds to:", a:"Frequency of data collection",
  w:["Risk reporting","Dimensions of risk","Aggregation and systems development"],
  why:"Who = reporting; What = dimensions of risk; How = aggregation/systems; When = frequency; Where = investment/position level."},
 {lo:'4.5.1', d:'M', q:"Which component of risk measurement specifies WHAT data is collected?", a:"Dimensions of risk",
  w:["Aggregation and systems development","Investment or position level","Risk reporting"],
  why:"Exam trap: WHAT data is collected = dimensions of risk. WHO gets reports = risk reporting; HOW = aggregation/systems; WHERE = investment or position level."},
 {lo:'4.5.1', d:'M', q:"LEVEL 3 assets in a pricing matrix are:", a:"Illiquid, valued by models with low confidence, typically valued quarterly",
  w:["The most liquid, priced daily","Based on observable data at high frequency","Government bonds only"],
  why:"Level 1 = liquid/high-frequency market data; Level 2 = observable but less frequent; Level 3 = model-based (capital statements, DCF, proxy indices) quarterly. Valuation is separated from the investment manager to avoid conflicts."},
 {lo:'4.5.2', d:'M', q:"Aggregating RISK across a portfolio differs from aggregating RETURNS because:", a:"Risk aggregation is nonlinear and depends on correlations; returns are a simple weighted average",
  w:["Returns require Monte Carlo simulation; risk does not","Risk is the simple sum of position risks","Returns depend on correlations; risk does not"],
  why:"Total risk ≠ sum of risks. Nonlinear exposures need simulations, stress tests, multifactor models — and qualitative risk systems for alternatives."},
 {lo:'4.5.2', d:'M', q:"Which is a listed mitigation of KEY PERSON risk?", a:"Extraordinary redemption rights linked to the key person's departure",
  w:["Concentrating decisions in one star manager","Cancelling the insurance to cut costs","Hiding departures from LPs"],
  why:"Mitigations: don't rely on one individual, key person insurance, extraordinary redemption rights, and a diversified portfolio of replaceable investments."},
 {lo:'4.5.2', d:'E', q:"EXCEPTION reports are generated:", a:"Only when risk measures breach predetermined parameters — to focus senior management attention",
  w:["Every day regardless of content","Only at year-end","Whenever performance is positive"],
  why:"Exception reporting optimizes the reporting process: detail gathered daily, escalated only on breaches."},
 {lo:'4.5.3', d:'M', q:"A manager WATCH LIST is used to:", a:"Track managers with performance or qualitative concerns until the concern is resolved or the investment is redeemed",
  w:["List the top-performing managers for marketing","Record all managers alphabetically","Schedule holiday cards"],
  why:"Part of the due diligence tracking matrix: descriptive info, key info, other info, watch list, and activity log; CCO may certify the qualitative measures."},
 {lo:'4.5.4', d:'M', q:"WEEKLY risk reports built from aggregated daily data typically show:", a:"Gross long, gross short, and net exposures plus margin-to-equity changes",
  w:["Only annual performance attribution","On-site visit summaries","Background check results"],
  why:"Daily: prices/positions/keyword searches. Weekly: exposures and leverage. Monthly: turnover and exposures at all levels, feeding watch lists."},
 {lo:'4.5.5', d:'M', q:"Best-practice ANNUAL review of an external manager includes:", a:"On-site visits (about every six months — one ops-focused, one investment DD) and background checks every three years",
  w:["A single phone call","Only reviewing the fund website","No documentation requirements"],
  why:"Annual reviews resemble initial due diligence: mandates and agreements reapproved, fees and performance analyzed, code of ethics and AML documented."},
 {lo:'4.5.6', d:'M', q:"Which is NOT one of the SEC Risk Alert's six cybersecurity examination areas?", a:"Marketing material design",
  w:["Governance and risk assessment","Vendor management","Incident response"],
  why:"The six areas: governance & risk assessment, access rights & controls, data loss prevention, vendor management, training, incident response."},
 {lo:'4.5.6', d:'M', q:"The EU's NIS Directive (compliance by May 2018) requires essential-service operators to:", a:"Identify critical systems, run penetration tests, train employees, and maintain an incident response plan",
  w:["Abolish all cloud storage","Report only to US regulators","Encrypt nothing below $1M AUM"],
  why:"NIS: national cybersecurity capabilities, EU-level cooperation, risk management and reporting. Asia regulates country-by-country (HK MA/SFC, Japan's three acts, Singapore's Cybersecurity Act)."},
 {lo:'4.5.7', d:'M', q:"The PREFERRED risk-management structure places the risk-manager role with:", a:"The CIO, strictly separated from other investment decisions",
  w:["The CEO in small firms (preferred everywhere)","The portfolio manager who knows the book best","An intern with a dashboard"],
  why:"Three models: CEO/president; COO/CFO; CIO. Preferred = CIO as dedicated risk manager — separation from the PM removes conflicts and keeps risk a priority."},
 {lo:'4.5.7', d:'E', q:"The investment process is described as primarily a:", a:"Risk process — linear gates (idea → due diligence → committee → board) each applying risk identification and measurement",
  w:["Sales process","Tax process","Marketing funnel"],
  why:"At each stage risk is identified, measured, managed bottom-up and aggregated to the total portfolio; risk analysts monitor dashboards daily and escalate via exception reporting."},
